  <article class="homepage_content">
    <div>
      <h1 class="homepage_title">Search EThOS (E-Theses Online Service)</h1>
      <p class="homepage_intro">Search the metadata of over 650,000 UK doctoral theses.</p>

      <%= render partial: 'catalog/search_form' %>

      <div class="flex-row flex-layout-space-between width-100 welcome-announcements-container">
        <div class="announcements display-flex flex-column">
          <header class="flex-column gap-1">
            <h2 role="heading" aria-level="3" class="announcements-item-title mat-headline-medium">Introducing the restored EThOS service</h2>
          </header>
          <article>
            <p class="homepage_intro">EThOS (eTheses Online Service) is an open access discovery platform for UK doctoral theses, managed by the British Library. This is a restored version of EThOS following a cyber-attack on the British Library in 2023. The platform holds metadata for theses held in UK Institutional Repositories.
            <br/>
            <br/>
            In the platform you can find descriptions of over 650,000 theses from UK universities from the 1700s to the present day. Over 400,000 of these theses are openly available for download from the institutional repository of the university. In many metadata records in EThOS you will find a button ‘Access thesis from university’.  This links to the metadata record of the thesis in the university’s repository, where it is possible to download the thesis, if the university has made it available.
            <br/><br/>
            <b>Please note:</b>
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li>while we are continuing to update the platform following the cyber-attack, there will be an initial backlog of content to work through</li>
              <li>not all theses are available for download from the institutional repository of the university.</li>
            </ul>
            <p class="homepage_intro">
              For further details, please refer to our <%= link_to 'FAQs', hyrax.help_path, aria: current_page?(hyrax.help_path) ? {current: 'page'} : nil %> and <%= link_to t(:'hyrax.controls.about'), hyrax.about_path, aria: current_page?(hyrax.about_path) ? {current: 'page'} : nil %> sections.
            </p>
          </article>

        </div>
      </div>

    </div>
  </article>

